\begin_layout Theorem
[Representation theorem] If the four axioms presented above hold, then there
 exists a utility index 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 such that ranking according to expected utility accords with actual preference
 over lotteries.
 In other words, if we compare two lotteries, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 represented by the probability vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $P=(p_{s})_{s=1,...,S}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=(q_{s})_{s=1,...,S}$
\end_inset

 over the same set of outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}=(1,...,S)$
\end_inset

 then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{1}\preceq L_{2}\Leftrightarrow\underset{s=1}{\overset{s=S}{\sum}}p_{s}u(c_{s})\leq\underset{s=1}{\overset{s=S}{\sum}}q_{s}u(c_{s})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Proof: See pp.176-178 of the Mas-Colell or p.
 76 of Kreps.
 The easiest proof assumes there exist a worst, 
\begin_inset Formula $w,$
\end_inset

 and a best lottery, 
\begin_inset Formula $t,$
\end_inset

 and defines the utility of any lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as the number such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim u(p)t+(1-u(p))w.$
\end_inset

 By continuity, that number exists and is unique.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 itself is defined over the set of consequence 
\begin_inset Formula $C:(a,b,c)$
\end_inset

, and each of those consequences can be ascribed an utility according to
 the above method.
 Define thus 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)$
\end_inset

 the utility of consequence 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 for example.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim p(a)a+p(b)b+p(c)c$
\end_inset

 (by reducibility).
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim u(a)t+(1-u(a))w$
\end_inset

, and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 By the independence axiom, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim(p(a)u(a)+p(b)u(b)+p(c)u(c))t+(1-p(a)u(a)-p(b)u(b)-p(c)u(c))w.$
\end_inset

 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(p)=p(a)u(a)+p(b)u(b)+p(c)u(c).$
\end_inset

 
