\begin_layout Subsection
Process violation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common example of violation of transitivity is the 
\begin_inset Quotes grd
\end_inset

P-bet, $-bet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following two lotteries:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
P-bet: $30 with 90% probability, and zero otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
$-bet: $100 with 30% probability and zero otherwise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An agent is first asked which lottery they would prefer playing, and then
 asked what price they would buy a ticket to play the P-bet or the $-bet.
 Notice that in this example, the expected payoff of the $-bet is higher
 than that of P-bet, but the $-bet is also more risky (lower probability
 to win).
 This may be why people tend to choose to play the P-bet over the $-bet.
 Yet, the same people are ready to pay 
\emph on
more
\emph default
 for a ticket to play the $-bet than for a ticket to play a P-bet.
 Said in another way, although when directly asked, they would choose the
 P-bet, they are willing to pay a lower certainty-equivalent amount of money
 for a P-bet than they do for a $-bet.
 For example, they might express a preference for the P-bet, but be ready
 only to pay $25 to play the P-bet while being ready to pay $27 for the
 $-bet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many have claimed that this violates the transitivity axiom.
 The argument is that one must be indifferent between the certainty-equivalent
 amount (
\begin_inset Quotes grd
\end_inset

price
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) of the bet and playing it, so that in utility terms, taking the example
 above again, I would have 
\begin_inset Formula $U(P-bet)=U(\$25)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\$-bet)=U(\$27)$
\end_inset

.
 By monotonicity, since more money is better than less money, 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\$27)>U(\$25)$
\end_inset

 and so we should conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\$-bet)>U(P-bet)$
\end_inset

.
 Yet, when asked directly, people usually prefer the 
\begin_inset Formula $P-bet$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\$-bet$
\end_inset

, implying 
\begin_inset Formula $U(P-bet)>U(\$-bet).$
\end_inset

 Thus, the intransitivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the question is whether this 
\begin_inset Quotes grd
\end_inset

intransitivity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

is not simply due to overpricing of $-bets, i.e.
