\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
RDEUT differs from PT in that it requires that the sum of probabilies over
 a whole set of events be equal to one.
 This is doe as follows: If one orders events from the least to the most
 preferred, ( 
\begin_inset Formula $a\prec b\prec c\prec d$
\end_inset

), then one writes the utility of lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $L=(p_{a},p_{b},p_{c},p_{d})$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(L)=f(p_{a})u(a)+f(p_{b})u(b)+f(p_{c})u(c)+f(p_{d})u(d)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f(p_{a}) & =\pi(p_{a})\\
f(p_{b}) & =\pi(p_{a}+p_{b})-\pi(p_{a})\\
f(p_{c}) & =\pi(p_{a}+p_{b}+p_{c})-\pi(p_{a}+p_{b})\\
f(p_{d}) & =1-\pi(p_{a}+p_{b}+p_{c})
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compared with PT, RDEUT guarantees that the sum of the probability weights
 assigned to each events sum up to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Check indeed that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p_{a})+f(p_{b})+f(p_{c})+f(p_{d})=1.$
\end_inset

 In RDEUT, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(.)$
\end_inset

 is a cumulative probability function, with outcomes added in the order
 of their preferences.
 
\end_layout

