\begin_layout Subsection
Regret theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regret theory differs from the above theories because it does not obtain
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $`$
\end_inset

utility function' but rather, a gain/loss function that evaluates by how
 much choosing a lottery over another and then comparing their outcome is
 expected to make one happy/unhappy.
 To the difference of other theories, regret theory explicitly takes into
 account the opportunity cost of making a decision.
 Decisions are not taken in a vacuum; making one decision precludes making
 another one.
 The theory is exposed in Loomes and Sugden (82, 86)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Loomes G.
 and R.
 Sugden, 1982, Regret Theory: An Alternative Theory of Rational Choice Under
 Uncertainty, The Economic Journal 92(368), 805-824.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Loomes G.
 and R.
 Sugden, 1986, Disappointment and Dynamic Consistency in Choice under Uncertaint
y, The Review of Economic Studies 53(2), 271-282.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and Sugden (85).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sugden R., 1985, Regret, recrimination and rationality, Theory and Decision
 19(1), 77-99.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Agents thus faced with alternative lotteries do not seek to maximize expected
 utility but rather to minimize expected regret (or maximize expected rejoicing)
 from their choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, suppose lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 has probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{1},..,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 while lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{1},..,q_{n})$
\end_inset

 over the same finite set of outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},...,x_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Expected rejoice/regret from choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E(r(p,q))=\underset{i}{\sum}\underset{j}{\sum}p_{i}q_{j}r(x_{i},x_{j})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}q_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 in lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 in lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 will be chosen over lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $E(r(p,q))$
\end_inset

 is positive and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 will be chosen over 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $E(r(p,q))$
\end_inset

 is negative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x_{i},x_{j})=u(x_{i})-u(x_{j})$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $E(r(p,q))$
\end_inset

 is simply the difference in expected utility between lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and regret theory leads to exactly the same decision as EUT.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under regret theory:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $r(x,y)$
\end_inset

 is increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 so that the higher the good outcome, the higher the rejoicing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $r(x,y)=-r(y,x),$
\end_inset

 so that regret/rejoice is symmetric: Getting the good outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 rather than the bad outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 produces the same amount of rejoicing than the amount of regret induced
 by getting the symmetric outcome.
 The expected rejoice at a gain is the same as the expected regret at a
 same sized loss,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $r(x,y)>r(x,z)+r(z,y)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x>z>y$
\end_inset

, that is the rejoicing increases more than proportionately with the difference
 in outcome.
 I rejoice more if I gain $100 rather than $0 than the sum of rejoicing
 if I gain $50 rather than $0 and $100 rather than $50, even though the
 result is the same.
 Consider for example how French people would react if their rugby team
 beat Australia (pride, celebration), compared to how they would react if
 France beat New Zealand (the usual...), and New Zealand beat Australia (no
 one cares, at least in France, except maybe in Toulouse...).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The advantage of the regret/rejoice model is that the 
\begin_inset Quotes grd
\end_inset

indifference curves
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 over lotteries derived from it can be intransitive, i.e.
 yield up preference reversals.
 From the beginning of the course, we know that this means indifference
 curves can cross 
\emph on
inside
\emph default
 the M-M triangle.
 Exercise 6 in 
\begin_inset Quotes els
\end_inset

Choice under Uncertainty
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

 shows that not only does RT allow for intransitive preferences, but it
 also mandates one specific direction in which preferences can be intransitive,
 i.e.
 while it would allow 
\begin_inset Formula $A\succ B\succ C\succ A,$
\end_inset

 it would not allow 
\begin_inset Formula $A\prec B\prec C\prec A.$
\end_inset

 This means that a test of RT is to check that intransitiveness, when it
 occurs, occurs in one direction only.
 Experiments tend to bear this out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main issue with RT is that while comparisons between two lotteries are
 relatively easy under its setting, comparisons between several lotteries
 are much more involved.
 For example, while it is easy to model the choice between (marriage, no
 marriage), it is more difficult to model the choice between (marriage,
 civil partnership, none of the above).
 Of course, one could divide the comparison between those three lotteries
 into three comparisons between two lotteries, but one then loses most of
 the point of modeling the effect of regret on lottery choices.
\end_layout

